1 use of the Epinephrine injectors or the inhalers and spacers or
2 holding chambers.
3 E. The school district may maintain at each school a minimum of
4 two Epinephrine injectors devices and two inhalers with spacers or
5 holding chambers in a secure location. Provided, however, that
6 nothing in this section shall be construed as creating or imposing a
7 duty on a school district to maintain Epinephrine injectors or
8 inhalers with spacers or holding chambers at a school site or sites.
9 F. In the event a student is believed to be having an
10 anaphylactic reaction or respiratory distress, a school employee
11 shall contact 911 as soon as possible. If Epinephrine is
12 administered to a student, a school employee shall contact 911 as
13 soon as possible. The school district shall notify the parent or
14 guardian of any student who experiences a possible allergic reaction
15 as soon as possible.
16 G. The State Board of Education, in consultation with the State
17 Board of Health, shall develop model policies which school districts
18 may shall use in compliance with this section. The model policies
19 shall include, at a minimum, required annual training for teachers
20 and school employees who are directly responsible for students on
21 the topics of food allergies, recognizing anaphylaxis, and
22 instruction on how to administer Epinephrine. The training shall be
23 completed before the school year begins or upon hiring the teacher
24 or school employee. Documentation certifying completion of the
ENGR. H. B. NO. 2047 Page 5

1 requ ired training shall be retained in the personnel file of the
2 teacher or school employee. The training may be provided online or
3 in person by the school nurse or a recognized food allergy and
4 anaphylaxis training program.
5 H. The State Board of Education, in consultation with the State
6 Board of Health, shall promulgate rules to implement this section.
7 I. As used in this section:
8 1. "Medication" means a metered dose inhaler or a dry powder
9 inhaler to alleviate asthmatic symptoms, prescribed by a physician
10 and having an individual label, an anaphylaxis medication used to
11 treat anaphylaxis including but not limited to Epinephrine injectors
12 prescribed by a physician and having an individual label, or
13 replacement pancreatic enzymes prescribed by a physician and having
14 an individual label; and
15 2. "Self-administration" means a student's use of medication
16 pursuant to prescription or written direction from a physician.;
17 3. "Respiratory distress" means the perceived or actual
18 presence of coughing, wheezing or shortness of breath; and
19 4. "Inhaler" means a device that delivers a bronchodilator to
20 alleviate symptoms of respiratory distress that is manufactured in
21 the form of a metered-dose inhaler or dry-powder inhaler and that
22 may include a spacer or holding chamber that attaches to the inhaler
23 to improve the delivery of the bronchodilator.
